WEBVTT

00:06.165 --> 00:08.291
Can I borrow some money?
I'm going to sink our coal pit.

00:08.708 --> 00:09.749
Of course, you can.

00:10.957 --> 00:13.416
MAN: Thomas Ainsworth,
he's asking if might see you

00:13.499 --> 00:14.374
for just a few moments.

00:14.666 --> 00:16.332
I'm giving you the opportunity
to leave here,

00:16.416 --> 00:19.416
and return to Norwich with
something you barely deserve.

00:19.708 --> 00:20.749
Your reputation.

00:21.332 --> 00:23.124
MARIAN LISTER:
Mr. Abbot is coming to tea.

00:23.207 --> 00:24.332
-Will you be here?
-No.

00:24.541 --> 00:27.708
The family are concerned
about a relationship

00:27.791 --> 00:29.499
with Miss Lister
and Miss Walker.

00:29.583 --> 00:32.082
Don't let them poison you
against us.

00:33.624 --> 00:35.082
Would you have any objection

00:35.165 --> 00:36.833
to taking the sacrament
together?

00:36.915 --> 00:39.332
ANN WALKER: I can't do this
anymore! It's wrong!

00:39.416 --> 00:42.874
You understand nothing about me.
Absolutely nothing!

00:43.457 --> 00:45.666
Miss Lister knows we're stealing
her coal.

00:45.957 --> 00:48.499
If she wants to start
running with the big dogs,

00:49.624 --> 00:50.915
she's gonna have to find
what it's like

00:50.999 --> 00:52.666
when they really start biting.

00:57.957 --> 00:58.874
[TV static drones]

00:58.957 --> 01:02.040
[bright tone]

01:02.124 --> 01:05.082
[somber music]

01:05.165 --> 01:06.291
♪ ♪

01:06.374 --> 01:08.374
[animal vocalizes in distance]

01:10.457 --> 01:12.082
♪ ♪

01:12.165 --> 01:14.874
[wings flapping]

01:14.957 --> 01:15.957
[bird vocalizes]

01:16.040 --> 01:17.708
[wings flapping]

01:17.791 --> 01:22.541
♪ ♪

01:22.624 --> 01:25.082
- I don't believe
the Reform Act

01:25.165 --> 01:26.249
went far enough!

01:26.332 --> 01:29.082
I'm not by inclination
a radical,

01:29.165 --> 01:32.249
but the fact is people
are becoming radicalized,

01:32.332 --> 01:36.666
whether people like us
are reconciled to it or not,

01:36.749 --> 01:40.082
and those of us who do,
perhaps, live in the past...

01:40.165 --> 01:41.249
- [sighs]

01:41.332 --> 01:43.249
- Need to see which way
the wind's blowing,

01:43.332 --> 01:44.833
or you watch,

01:44.915 --> 01:47.249
we'll have more trouble
than we know what to do with.

01:47.332 --> 01:51.249
Now, "revolution" is, uh,
a very emotive word.

01:51.332 --> 01:52.499
I understand that.

01:54.957 --> 01:58.207
- Oh!
- Shh, shh.

01:58.291 --> 02:01.207
[clock chiming]

02:01.291 --> 02:03.457
It's nothing.

02:03.541 --> 02:05.541
I just need some warm water.

02:09.666 --> 02:11.624
I just need some water.

02:11.708 --> 02:14.541
Can you bring it up
to my room?

02:14.624 --> 02:16.374
- Yes, ma'am.

02:22.666 --> 02:24.416
[footsteps approaching]

02:29.791 --> 02:31.291
- [groans loudly]

02:31.374 --> 02:33.874
[panting]

02:55.541 --> 02:58.416
[footsteps approaching]

03:09.040 --> 03:11.499
[water trickling]

03:11.583 --> 03:12.999
[container clangs]

03:15.082 --> 03:16.708
- What's happened, ma'am?

03:16.791 --> 03:19.165
- [sighs]
Nothing.

03:19.249 --> 03:20.666
- Do you want me to...

03:20.749 --> 03:23.749
- No.

03:23.833 --> 03:25.624
Thank you.

03:25.708 --> 03:27.499
I'll do it.

03:27.583 --> 03:28.874
[sniffs]

03:32.416 --> 03:35.040
- Can I get you some brandy?

03:35.124 --> 03:36.374
- No.

03:38.957 --> 03:42.957
- Should I tell your aunt
or your father that you...

03:43.040 --> 03:45.374
- No.
Will you just...

03:45.457 --> 03:47.332
- Ma'am.

03:47.416 --> 03:49.374
- Just let me know
when Mr. Abbott's gone.

03:49.457 --> 03:52.082
- Should I not send
for Dr. Kenny?

03:52.165 --> 03:53.999
- [chuckles]
No.

03:56.624 --> 03:58.499
No.

04:03.124 --> 04:05.332
- There was a package
came for you.

04:05.416 --> 04:07.374
Shall I fetch it?
It's in your study.

04:07.457 --> 04:09.457
- Mm.

04:09.541 --> 04:11.249
[sniffs]

04:11.332 --> 04:14.291
[somber music]

04:14.374 --> 04:21.124
♪ ♪

04:21.207 --> 04:24.332
Go on.
You've got things to do.

04:24.416 --> 04:28.957
♪ ♪

04:29.040 --> 04:30.666
[door clicks shut]

04:30.749 --> 04:37.833
♪ ♪

04:58.583 --> 04:59.957
[gags]

05:00.040 --> 05:02.957
[jaunty music]

05:03.040 --> 05:10.082
♪ ♪

05:36.124 --> 05:39.374
- Fell off a wall?

05:39.457 --> 05:40.708
- It was dark.

05:40.791 --> 05:43.749
- What was she doing
on a wall in the dark?

05:43.833 --> 05:45.165
- Walking on it.

05:45.249 --> 05:47.124
- Yes, why?
- Because it was there.

05:47.207 --> 05:49.165
- Exactly.
- Like Mont Blanc.

05:49.249 --> 05:50.541
- Which wall?

05:50.624 --> 05:53.541
- The one--the one coming back
from Lightcliffe

05:53.624 --> 05:54.915
along the Leeds road.

05:54.999 --> 05:58.332
- Not that one that falls away
15 feet on the other side?

05:58.416 --> 05:59.666
- Well, it wouldn't
have been worth doing

05:59.749 --> 06:00.666
if it was any lower.

06:00.749 --> 06:01.749
- In all that wind?

06:01.833 --> 06:03.332
Who on earth
put you up to that?

06:03.416 --> 06:04.791
- No one. Me.

06:04.874 --> 06:06.416
Anyway, that's why I didn't

06:06.499 --> 06:07.915
come down for dinner
last night.

06:07.999 --> 06:10.165
I was feeling bilious.

06:10.249 --> 06:13.791
- Did it seem like a good idea
at the time?

06:13.874 --> 06:15.791
- Wasn't as dangerous
as that time I walked

06:15.874 --> 06:17.291
across the parapet
of North Bridge

06:17.374 --> 06:18.416
that time it flooded.

06:18.499 --> 06:20.082
- When did you do that?

06:20.165 --> 06:21.791
- 1815.

06:21.874 --> 06:24.624
I had to.
I had to get into Halifax.

06:24.708 --> 06:26.457
I was running out of ink.

06:26.541 --> 06:28.249
- Well, you missed
Mr. Abbott.

06:28.332 --> 06:29.624
- Who?

06:31.207 --> 06:32.999
Oh.

06:33.082 --> 06:35.791
Was that yesterday?

06:35.874 --> 06:38.666
Yes? How was it?

06:38.749 --> 06:41.541
- It went very well.

06:44.124 --> 06:45.708
- Are you sure?

06:45.791 --> 06:49.416
- How is Miss Walker?

06:49.499 --> 06:50.874
- Oh, she's...

06:50.957 --> 06:53.915
[melancholy music]

06:53.999 --> 06:55.708
♪ ♪

06:55.791 --> 06:58.499
Sorry, I-I think
I'm going to be sick.

06:58.583 --> 07:05.666
♪ ♪

07:07.541 --> 07:09.165
[moans]

07:18.666 --> 07:19.749
- Those aren't the sorts
of injuries

07:19.833 --> 07:21.915
anyone gets
from falling off a wall.

07:21.999 --> 07:27.833
♪ ♪

07:27.915 --> 07:29.332
If you could be present
next time,

07:29.416 --> 07:30.999
when he brings his mother,

07:31.082 --> 07:32.499
I'd be grateful.

07:32.583 --> 07:38.915
♪ ♪

07:39.999 --> 07:41.791
- Dearest Mary,

07:41.874 --> 07:44.624
since I am more eager
than ever to be off,

07:44.708 --> 07:47.541
I am keen to acquire a groom,
which, you will recall,

07:47.624 --> 07:49.791
I have been without since
George Playforth's demise

07:49.874 --> 07:51.583
at Langton earlier this year,

07:51.666 --> 07:53.374
when he was shot
out of a tree.

07:53.457 --> 07:55.249
Do think about this for me.

07:55.332 --> 07:57.666
I should like
a good, strong, English groom

07:57.749 --> 08:00.833
who would do
anything in the world for me.

08:00.915 --> 08:02.207
A little enterprise necessary,

08:02.291 --> 08:03.833
otherwise, he will soon tire
of the Continent

08:03.915 --> 08:06.124
long before I am likely
to have any inducement

08:06.207 --> 08:08.541
to return from it.

08:08.624 --> 08:10.124
- Dearest Fred,

08:10.207 --> 08:12.374
there is a man
who might suit.

08:12.457 --> 08:14.583
He has lived two years
with our neighbors,

08:14.666 --> 08:17.291
the Kinnersleys,
and is a native of Lawton.

08:17.374 --> 08:19.165
A remarkably handsome
young man

08:19.249 --> 08:20.915
called Thomas Beech.

08:20.999 --> 08:23.291
He understands
horses and carriages

08:23.374 --> 08:25.457
and would much like
to go abroad.

08:25.541 --> 08:26.957
He has a good character

08:27.040 --> 08:29.082
and I believe would do
anything in the world

08:29.165 --> 08:31.291
to make himself useful
to you.

08:31.374 --> 08:33.332
Tell me, Fred,

08:33.416 --> 08:35.624
is it Miss Walker
of Crow Nest

08:35.708 --> 08:37.749
with whom you plan to travel?

08:37.833 --> 08:40.457
- No, Mary, it isn't.

08:40.541 --> 08:42.499
- You mentioned her twice
in your last

08:42.583 --> 08:44.708
as "my friend"...

08:44.791 --> 08:46.249
- Did I?

08:46.332 --> 08:49.457
- And as you are not wont
to bestow the title lightly,

08:49.541 --> 08:51.082
I am puzzled to understand

08:51.165 --> 08:52.874
how she has
so quickly succeeded

08:52.957 --> 08:55.957
in adding herself
to the list so designated.

08:56.040 --> 08:58.666
[jaunty music]

08:58.749 --> 09:01.165
- [sighs]

09:01.249 --> 09:08.291
♪ ♪

09:09.874 --> 09:11.291
My dearest Mary,

09:11.374 --> 09:12.874
it sounds as if
your Thomas Beech

09:12.957 --> 09:15.082
would suit me
down to the ground.

09:15.165 --> 09:17.207
♪ ♪

09:17.291 --> 09:18.874
Hmm.
- Oh.

09:18.957 --> 09:21.124
- Turns out Mariana
may have found me a groom.

09:21.207 --> 09:22.124
- Oh.

09:22.207 --> 09:23.541
- I'll put him on wages
straightaway,

09:23.624 --> 09:26.124
and then I can be
off again whenever--

09:26.207 --> 09:29.457
your health permitting...
and the weather.

09:29.541 --> 09:31.833
- Uh, Mr. Rawson's servant
left you a note

09:31.915 --> 09:33.708
while you were upstairs.

09:36.583 --> 09:39.624
- Which Mr. Rawson?
- Jeremiah.

09:55.374 --> 09:56.833
What does he want?

10:00.749 --> 10:04.583
- To discuss the terms
of the coal lease... again.

10:06.874 --> 10:09.915
[sighing]

10:14.124 --> 10:15.749
- You all right?

10:17.165 --> 10:18.915
- Hmm.

10:22.833 --> 10:25.791
- I couldn't warm
to Mr. Abbott,

10:25.874 --> 10:28.249
much as I wanted to.

10:28.332 --> 10:32.791
I found him abrasive
and a know-all.

10:32.874 --> 10:37.749
But if she likes him,
and she seems to,

10:37.833 --> 10:40.207
and he has done
very well for himself,

10:40.291 --> 10:43.874
surely that's something.

10:46.457 --> 10:48.207
It would be
a great comfort to me

10:48.291 --> 10:50.416
to know you're both settled.

10:51.874 --> 10:53.207
- Hmm.

10:55.249 --> 10:57.124
I'm afraid it may all be off

10:57.207 --> 10:59.583
between me and Miss Walker.

11:01.749 --> 11:04.708
Us setting up home together.

11:07.708 --> 11:10.999
I think she may be too nervous
and insipid for me.

11:11.082 --> 11:13.791
It's a shame, because I, um...

11:15.749 --> 11:17.374
I'd become rather more fond
of her

11:17.457 --> 11:19.165
than I ever imagined I would.

11:20.957 --> 11:22.040
[sighs]

11:22.124 --> 11:25.583
I really had started to think
that we could both

11:25.666 --> 11:26.583
be good for one another,

11:26.666 --> 11:29.833
irrespective of all her money.

11:29.915 --> 11:32.332
[sighs]

11:32.416 --> 11:34.374
And she's so sweet.

11:34.457 --> 11:36.541
She's so good-natured.

11:36.624 --> 11:38.040
She's so kind...

11:38.124 --> 11:40.332
[sighs]
And she...

11:43.624 --> 11:45.165
She looks up to me.

11:45.249 --> 11:46.999
I certainly do her more good

11:47.082 --> 11:49.833
than any single one
of her tribe of relations.

11:49.915 --> 11:52.457
- Well, then, what's...

11:52.541 --> 11:55.374
- Them.

11:55.457 --> 11:56.374
All of them.

11:56.457 --> 11:59.249
They filled her head
with nonsense...

11:59.332 --> 12:00.708
[sighs]

12:00.791 --> 12:02.165
Nasty nonsense about me,

12:02.249 --> 12:05.583
till she doesn't know
whether she's coming or going.

12:05.666 --> 12:08.249
She just wants some courage,

12:08.332 --> 12:11.291
the courage to follow her...

12:15.124 --> 12:16.624
Her instincts,

12:16.708 --> 12:18.040
but she won't.

12:18.124 --> 12:20.624
She'll just stay there,
surrounded by them,

12:20.708 --> 12:23.791
and her world will just get
smaller and sadder

12:23.874 --> 12:25.374
until one day,
there'll be nothing left.

12:25.457 --> 12:28.999
She'll be as dry as a stick,
and then she'll just disappear.

12:34.499 --> 12:38.207
And I could make her so happy.

12:38.291 --> 12:40.207
[sighs]
But what's the point?

12:40.291 --> 12:41.915
She barely has the courage
to step outside

12:41.999 --> 12:44.957
her own front door.

12:45.040 --> 12:48.708
So anyway, that said, it...

12:50.915 --> 12:52.499
It's all off.

12:54.332 --> 12:56.833
- Well, then,
who will you travel with?

12:56.915 --> 12:58.874
- No one.

12:58.957 --> 13:01.999
- You mean alone?

13:02.082 --> 13:04.583
Do people do that? Ladies?

13:04.666 --> 13:05.749
- [sighs]

13:05.833 --> 13:09.874
No, but I'll take Eugénie
and this groom,

13:09.957 --> 13:14.874
this Thomas Beech,
to Paris,

13:14.957 --> 13:17.124
and I'll take it from there.

13:17.207 --> 13:21.499
I'll see what providence
throws at me this time.

13:21.583 --> 13:23.499
[warm music]

13:23.583 --> 13:28.624
- It's a big step for her,
moving in here,

13:28.708 --> 13:31.499
and if her family
aren't sympathetic,

13:31.583 --> 13:34.457
maybe it's for the best.

13:34.541 --> 13:36.291
♪ ♪

13:36.374 --> 13:37.874
[footsteps approaching]

13:37.957 --> 13:40.082
- Ma'am, Mr. Washington's here.

13:40.165 --> 13:41.749
- Tell him I'll see him
in the hall.

13:41.833 --> 13:43.957
- Yes, ma'am.

13:44.040 --> 13:47.541
♪ ♪

13:47.624 --> 13:49.332
- [sighs]

13:49.416 --> 13:56.499
♪ ♪

14:00.332 --> 14:02.124
- Been in the wars, ma'am?

14:02.207 --> 14:04.541
- After a fashion.

14:04.624 --> 14:06.332
- So, uh, it's all sorted out
for Friday

14:06.416 --> 14:07.708
down at the Stag's Head.

14:07.791 --> 14:09.207
There's been
plenty of interest.

14:09.291 --> 14:10.499
The Mann brothers,
particularly,

14:10.583 --> 14:11.833
very keen to put in a bid.

14:11.915 --> 14:14.666
- I want to put
the pit-sinking on hold.

14:14.749 --> 14:15.583
- Sorry?

14:15.666 --> 14:18.124
- The Rawsons
got back to me, finally.

14:18.207 --> 14:19.708
Turns out they do still want

14:19.791 --> 14:21.666
to discuss the terms
of the lease.

14:21.749 --> 14:25.915
- But... I thought the decision
had been made, ma'am,

14:25.999 --> 14:26.999
to sink the pit.

14:27.082 --> 14:28.499
Surely, you've given them

14:28.583 --> 14:30.791
more than enough time
to respond.

14:30.874 --> 14:34.791
Are they not...
messing you about?

14:34.874 --> 14:37.040
It's not like you
to go back on a decision

14:37.124 --> 14:38.874
once it's been made.

14:40.457 --> 14:43.583
- My circumstances
and my priorities

14:43.666 --> 14:45.332
have altered somewhat

14:45.416 --> 14:47.416
over the last few days,

14:47.499 --> 14:49.374
so I want to pause
and reassess

14:49.457 --> 14:53.541
and be certain
I'm making the right choices.

14:53.624 --> 14:56.165
- Right.

14:56.249 --> 14:59.541
- So how did Suzannah get on
with Miss Hebden?

14:59.624 --> 15:01.708
- Oh, she's gone to meet her
just this morning, ma'am.

15:01.791 --> 15:03.040
That's--thank you.

15:03.124 --> 15:06.374
That's--we're--we're very
grateful for that introduction.

15:06.457 --> 15:09.374
[metal clattering]

15:09.457 --> 15:12.374
[gentle music]

15:12.457 --> 15:14.249
- Hello.

15:14.332 --> 15:16.499
- Miss Washington.

15:16.583 --> 15:18.749
Uh, sorry.
Am I blocking the lane?

15:18.833 --> 15:21.416
- Oh, no, no,
you're all right.

15:21.499 --> 15:24.249
- This keeps busting.

15:25.541 --> 15:27.291
You off into Halifax?

15:27.374 --> 15:29.416
- Yeah.

15:29.499 --> 15:31.583
- I can give you a lift.

15:31.666 --> 15:33.915
- Oh, that's very kind of you.

15:33.999 --> 15:35.624
- Just gotta drop this one off
at Bateman's.

15:35.708 --> 15:36.915
Won't take five minutes.

15:36.999 --> 15:38.207
- Oh, no, I don't want to know

15:38.291 --> 15:39.666
what Mr. Bateman's
gonna do to it!

15:39.749 --> 15:42.249
[pig squeals, snorts]

15:42.332 --> 15:43.999
- They say it's the best end
a pig could have,

15:44.082 --> 15:46.666
at Mr. Bateman's hands.

15:46.749 --> 15:48.416
- How?

15:48.499 --> 15:49.957
- He's quick.

15:50.040 --> 15:51.165
They know nowt about it,

15:51.249 --> 15:53.915
and they become the finest
hams and--and sausages

15:53.999 --> 15:55.332
and pies in Halifax.

15:56.791 --> 15:58.999
- I've got an appointment
with Miss Hebden

15:59.082 --> 16:00.791
about an apprenticeship,

16:00.874 --> 16:02.291
learning to make dresses.

16:02.374 --> 16:04.249
If she likes me, she'll want me
to start Monday.

16:04.332 --> 16:06.957
25 shillings a year,
plus board.

16:07.040 --> 16:09.583
- Oh, well, that's... good.
- Yeah, but...

16:11.082 --> 16:14.291
I don't want to go.

16:14.374 --> 16:16.040
- Why?

16:17.541 --> 16:19.708
- Well, I won't see anyone
all week,

16:19.791 --> 16:21.207
anyone I care about.

16:22.416 --> 16:23.666
- You'll see me.

16:23.749 --> 16:25.541
If Mr. Bateman
likes the merchandise,

16:25.624 --> 16:27.915
I'll be supplying
to him regularly.

16:27.999 --> 16:30.874
I might be down here
every five minutes.

16:30.957 --> 16:32.957
- Well, he'll like
the merchandise, all right.

16:33.040 --> 16:35.583
I've never seen
such a fine, handsome pig.

16:35.666 --> 16:37.915
What have you been
feeding him on?

16:37.999 --> 16:39.624
[light music]

16:39.708 --> 16:41.499
- All sorts.

16:41.583 --> 16:43.583
♪ ♪

16:43.666 --> 16:45.833
I can wait for you,
if you like.

16:45.915 --> 16:47.165
I can give you a lift back.

16:47.249 --> 16:49.332
- You don't want to be
hanging around, waiting for me.

16:49.416 --> 16:51.332
[both chattering]

16:51.416 --> 16:54.332
[clock ticking]

16:54.416 --> 16:55.749
[ominous music]

16:55.833 --> 16:57.874
- Hang the whores!

16:57.957 --> 16:59.583
[militaristic drumbeat]

16:59.666 --> 17:01.165
[raucous chatter]

17:01.249 --> 17:05.416
- Anyone who looks at a woman
with lustful intent

17:05.499 --> 17:10.207
has already committed adultery
with her in their heart.

17:10.291 --> 17:14.082
If your right eye
causes you to sin, rip it out!

17:14.165 --> 17:15.332
- Burn in hell!

17:15.416 --> 17:16.957
- If your right hand
causes you to sin...

17:17.040 --> 17:18.332
- Fear thy God!
- Cut it off!

17:18.416 --> 17:19.749
For it is better
that you lose

17:19.833 --> 17:21.165
one of your members

17:21.249 --> 17:24.332
than that your whole body
goes to hell!

17:24.416 --> 17:28.040
Hell was created
for the devil and his angels.

17:28.124 --> 17:31.666
It was a place made
for everlasting torment

17:31.749 --> 17:32.749
and punishment.

17:32.833 --> 17:35.124
You are going to die!

17:35.207 --> 17:37.291
- No! No! No!

17:37.374 --> 17:39.332
No!
[panting]

17:39.416 --> 17:40.791
- What's the matter?

17:40.874 --> 17:42.541
Ann, what on earth's
the matter?

17:42.624 --> 17:43.999
- I... I...

17:44.082 --> 17:45.791
- Oh, have you had
a nightmare?

17:45.874 --> 17:47.541
You've had a nightmare.

17:47.624 --> 17:49.541
- It was so real!

17:49.624 --> 17:52.040
[clock ticking]

17:52.124 --> 17:53.624
No.

17:53.708 --> 17:57.040
No, no. No.
Shush!

17:57.124 --> 17:58.332
Shush!
Stop it! Stop it!

17:58.416 --> 18:01.374
- Ann, Ann, what is it?

18:01.457 --> 18:02.541
What is it?
- Can't you--

18:02.624 --> 18:05.249
- What is it?
- Can't you hear them?

18:05.332 --> 18:06.416
Stop it! Stop it!
- Who?

18:06.499 --> 18:09.457
- [crying and panting]

18:09.541 --> 18:14.332
♪ ♪

18:17.249 --> 18:18.332
- John Abbott?

18:18.416 --> 18:20.749
Oh, yes, yes.

18:20.833 --> 18:22.082
He's making quite a name
for himself

18:22.165 --> 18:23.249
one way or another.

18:23.332 --> 18:25.666
A member of this, that,
and the other society,

18:25.749 --> 18:27.833
getting himself elected
into all sorts of committees

18:27.915 --> 18:28.915
within the town.

18:28.999 --> 18:29.957
Why?

18:30.040 --> 18:32.249
- Oh, he's sniffing
around Marian.

18:32.332 --> 18:33.999
- Is he?

18:34.082 --> 18:35.915
Well, that would make sense.

18:35.999 --> 18:36.833
- How?

18:36.915 --> 18:39.207
- Well, marrying
a bit of pedigree,

18:39.291 --> 18:40.708
not having any himself.

18:40.791 --> 18:42.332
[footsteps approaching]
Ah.

18:42.416 --> 18:43.583
Miss Lister.

18:43.666 --> 18:45.416
- Mr. Rawson.
- Oh, dear.

18:45.499 --> 18:46.541
What happened?

18:46.624 --> 18:48.957
- You should see
the other fellow.

18:49.040 --> 18:51.332
- [laughs]
- Hmm.

18:51.416 --> 18:53.541
He won't attempt
anything like that again,

18:53.624 --> 18:55.249
not in a hurry.

18:55.332 --> 18:56.499
Whoever paid him to do it

18:56.583 --> 18:57.999
should ask
for their money back.

18:58.082 --> 19:00.749
- She fell off a wall.

19:00.833 --> 19:03.624
- What were you doing
on a wall?

19:03.708 --> 19:05.957
- You wanted to discuss
the terms of the lease with me,

19:06.040 --> 19:07.124
again.

19:07.207 --> 19:09.374
- Yes.
- Why?

19:09.457 --> 19:11.416
Has your position altered?

19:11.499 --> 19:15.457
- No, but my brother thought...

19:15.541 --> 19:17.249
yours might have.

19:17.332 --> 19:20.332
- Did he? Why?

19:20.416 --> 19:22.291
[dark music]

19:22.374 --> 19:25.332
- Having had time
to dwell upon it.

19:25.416 --> 19:27.499
- Hmm.

19:27.583 --> 19:29.749
Well, oddly enough,
Mr. Rawson,

19:29.833 --> 19:31.291
my position has altered,

19:31.374 --> 19:32.499
but only very slightly,

19:32.583 --> 19:35.040
and not for any reason
your brother might fathom.

19:35.124 --> 19:36.999
I'm prepared to offer you
an abatement

19:37.082 --> 19:38.207
on the price of the upper bed.

19:38.291 --> 19:41.749
I'll offer it to you
at £129 and 10 shillings,

19:41.833 --> 19:43.915
and the reason for it
is a sincere desire

19:43.999 --> 19:44.833
to just get on with it,

19:44.915 --> 19:46.957
instead of going around
in circles.

19:47.040 --> 19:48.416
- That's--
- However...

19:48.499 --> 19:51.165
I'm not prepared to compromise
on the price of the lower bed,

19:51.249 --> 19:53.874
at £226 17 shillings
and sixpence,

19:53.957 --> 19:55.833
or any of the clauses.

19:55.915 --> 19:59.499
I would like access
to the pit at any time,

19:59.583 --> 20:01.457
and there will be
a £500 penalty incurred

20:01.541 --> 20:03.499
should any water be turned
on the pit

20:03.583 --> 20:05.249
at any point in the future.

20:05.332 --> 20:08.874
Neither of these requests
are unreasonable.

20:08.957 --> 20:10.291
Only someone
with something to hide

20:10.374 --> 20:12.124
would think they were.

20:13.457 --> 20:15.207
- I'll talk to him again.

20:15.291 --> 20:17.040
Perhaps an abatement
on the price of the upper bed

20:17.124 --> 20:19.749
will do the trick.

20:19.833 --> 20:21.624
[bell rings loudly]

20:21.708 --> 20:22.957
- Who knows?

20:23.040 --> 20:25.374
- [sighs]

20:25.457 --> 20:27.457
Captain Lister.

20:29.249 --> 20:30.833
Miss Lister.

20:34.332 --> 20:35.833
- I thought...

20:35.915 --> 20:37.999
are we not sinking our own pit?

20:39.708 --> 20:41.457
- I don't know what's going on
with Miss Walker.

20:41.541 --> 20:44.666
She blows hot and cold.
[sighs]

20:44.749 --> 20:46.791
It's not her fault, it's...

20:46.874 --> 20:49.416
difficult for her with--
with her family.

20:49.499 --> 20:50.541
They never leave her alone,

20:50.624 --> 20:54.082
and they put ridiculous ideas
in her head.

20:54.165 --> 20:56.499
She had said
I could borrow the money,

20:56.583 --> 20:58.082
but I can't.

20:58.165 --> 20:59.915
I don't want to.

20:59.999 --> 21:01.291
And I didn't fall off a wall.

21:01.374 --> 21:02.249
I was...

21:02.332 --> 21:04.082
[quietly]
Beaten up.

21:04.165 --> 21:05.249
- Sorry?

21:05.332 --> 21:08.624
- I was beaten up, by a thug,

21:08.708 --> 21:10.666
who someone must have paid
to do it--

21:10.749 --> 21:12.624
I assume by them,
the Rawsons.

21:12.708 --> 21:14.957
I mean, not him.
Not Jeremiah.

21:15.040 --> 21:16.249
I don't think Jeremiah

21:16.332 --> 21:17.583
could knock the skin
off a rice pudding,

21:17.666 --> 21:19.915
even if he paid someone
to do it, but Christopher--

21:19.999 --> 21:21.499
I wouldn't put anything
past Christopher,

21:21.583 --> 21:23.416
because he thinks
he can get away with anything.

21:23.499 --> 21:26.165
- But w-why?
W-why would he do that?

21:26.249 --> 21:27.416
- To warn me off!

21:27.499 --> 21:29.207
To make me sign
the blasted lease

21:29.291 --> 21:33.332
without insisting
on any inconvenient clauses,

21:33.416 --> 21:37.040
so he can take what he likes.

21:37.124 --> 21:40.457
You know it was him who caused
the accident as well,

21:40.541 --> 21:43.291
when little Henry Hardcastle
lost his leg?

21:43.374 --> 21:45.332
He was the idiot
driving the gig.

21:45.416 --> 21:46.708
He was seen!

21:48.708 --> 21:51.165
You did right
to warn me off coal.

21:51.249 --> 21:54.124
It's a nasty business.

21:54.207 --> 21:57.124
But I won't be beaten,
not by him.

21:57.207 --> 21:59.124
Not by anyone.

21:59.207 --> 22:00.082
- Ma'am,

22:00.165 --> 22:01.624
Miss Walker's manservant

22:01.708 --> 22:03.708
from Crow Nest is here

22:03.791 --> 22:05.124
with a message.

22:05.207 --> 22:08.165
[rising string music]

22:08.249 --> 22:15.332
♪ ♪

22:16.749 --> 22:18.999
- James?
- Ma'am.

22:19.082 --> 22:20.499
♪ ♪

22:20.583 --> 22:22.249
- What's the matter?

22:22.332 --> 22:25.249
[ominous music]

22:25.332 --> 22:31.207
♪ ♪

22:31.291 --> 22:32.749
[footsteps approaching]

22:32.833 --> 22:34.207
- Miss Lister.

22:34.291 --> 22:36.165
Thank goodness you're here.

22:38.666 --> 22:39.791
[door closes]

22:39.874 --> 22:41.541
- Miss Rawson.

22:41.624 --> 22:43.874
What happened to Miss Parkhill?

22:43.957 --> 22:45.999
- I-I think
she couldn't stand it.

22:46.082 --> 22:47.583
I didn't realize
Ann was so ill.

22:47.666 --> 22:48.666
None of us did.

22:48.749 --> 22:52.165
It's so much worse
than last time she was...

22:52.249 --> 22:54.207
like this.

22:54.291 --> 22:55.999
She had a terrible nightmare,
apparently--

22:56.082 --> 22:57.833
she won't tell anyone
what it was about--

22:57.915 --> 22:59.291
and then...

23:01.541 --> 23:06.040
She--she says she can
hear voices,

23:06.124 --> 23:09.291
in her room, in the night.

23:11.332 --> 23:14.291
[melancholy music]

23:14.374 --> 23:15.457
♪ ♪

23:15.541 --> 23:17.291
- Where is she?

23:17.374 --> 23:24.457
♪ ♪

23:40.416 --> 23:41.791
Ann.

23:41.874 --> 23:44.833
♪ ♪

23:44.915 --> 23:46.416
- [sighs]

23:46.499 --> 23:48.416
[moans, gasps]

23:48.499 --> 23:51.082
I thought you'd gone forever!

23:51.165 --> 23:52.499
I thought you'd given up on me.

23:52.583 --> 23:53.915
I thought
I'd never see you again!

23:53.999 --> 23:55.249
Anne, I'm sorry.

23:55.332 --> 23:56.666
[cries]
I'm sorry.

23:56.749 --> 23:59.833
I'm so sorry
about all the things I said.

23:59.915 --> 24:02.457
♪ ♪

24:02.541 --> 24:04.332
What happened to you?

24:04.416 --> 24:06.291
♪ ♪

24:06.374 --> 24:07.624
- Nothing.

24:07.708 --> 24:09.249
♪ ♪

24:09.332 --> 24:10.915
- Harriet's gone.

24:10.999 --> 24:13.541
I told her to leave.

24:13.624 --> 24:15.499
- People are worried about you.

24:17.124 --> 24:19.708
Tell me what's going on.

24:19.791 --> 24:21.165
- Don't leave me again.

24:21.249 --> 24:23.791
Promise me.

24:23.874 --> 24:30.416
♪ ♪

24:30.499 --> 24:33.874
- You said what we did
was repugnant and queer.

24:33.957 --> 24:36.374
- No, I love you.

24:36.457 --> 24:38.624
I want to be with you.
I want to marry you.

24:38.708 --> 24:40.249
- Shh, shh.
- I'll do everything--

24:40.332 --> 24:42.165
[quietly] I'll do
everything you said.

24:42.249 --> 24:43.791
I don't want to go abroad,

24:43.874 --> 24:45.624
not in the state I'm in
at the moment,

24:45.708 --> 24:46.624
but everything else.

24:46.708 --> 24:49.374
- No, we need
to get you better first.

24:49.457 --> 24:52.082
- Don't leave me again.
Promise me.

24:53.957 --> 24:56.541
- I'll do what I can--
- Promise me.

24:59.374 --> 25:02.957
- I'll do what I can for you.

25:03.040 --> 25:05.374
- Will you stay tonight?

25:05.457 --> 25:07.207
Please stay tonight.

25:07.291 --> 25:08.666
I need you.

25:08.749 --> 25:11.165
I need you here,
because you see,

25:11.249 --> 25:15.999
some very strange things
have been happening,

25:16.082 --> 25:17.791
and no one believes me,

25:17.874 --> 25:20.165
but you will.

25:20.249 --> 25:21.207
You'll hear them.

25:21.291 --> 25:23.124
If you--if you stay
in the room tonight,

25:23.207 --> 25:25.332
you'll hear them.

25:25.416 --> 25:26.624
- Who will I hear?

25:26.708 --> 25:29.249
- They're--they're--
they're spirits.

25:31.332 --> 25:33.040
Something to do

25:33.124 --> 25:35.332
with the clock on the landing.

25:35.416 --> 25:37.124
[clock ticking in distance]

25:37.207 --> 25:38.165
I know, Anne.

25:38.249 --> 25:40.833
I know--
I know that sounds bizarre,

25:40.915 --> 25:44.457
but I'm not making it up.

25:44.541 --> 25:47.207
I don't make things up.

25:56.124 --> 25:58.040
- Ma'am.

25:58.124 --> 25:59.957
Ma'am?

26:01.874 --> 26:02.957
Miss Lister? Ma'am?

26:03.040 --> 26:05.124
- [snorts]
[dog growls]

26:05.207 --> 26:06.708
- A note from Miss Lister.

26:06.791 --> 26:08.374
The servant from Crow Nest
brought it.

26:08.457 --> 26:09.957
- Oh. Thank you.

26:13.583 --> 26:15.165
- He's waiting in the kitchen
for Eugénie

26:15.249 --> 26:16.999
to pack
Miss Lister's overnight bag

26:17.082 --> 26:18.749
if there's any reply.

26:18.833 --> 26:21.499
- No, no.
No reply, thank you.

26:23.499 --> 26:25.165
[sighs]

26:27.165 --> 26:30.999
She's staying over at Crow Nest
for the night.

26:31.082 --> 26:31.999
[sighs]

26:32.082 --> 26:34.165
Thought it was all off
with Miss Walker.

26:35.833 --> 26:37.332
- Mm.

26:44.165 --> 26:45.708
- Where is Miss Pierre from?

26:45.791 --> 26:48.332
- Oh, can never remember.

26:48.416 --> 26:50.124
Where's she from again--
Eugénie?

26:50.207 --> 26:52.541
- Oh, is it Dieppe?

26:52.624 --> 26:53.624
Rouen, summat?

26:53.708 --> 26:56.082
- We're not overly impressed,
Mr. Mackenzie,

26:56.165 --> 26:57.624
between you and me.

26:57.708 --> 26:59.624
Are we, Mrs. Cordingley?

26:59.708 --> 27:02.082
- She's... [clears throat]
very pretty.

27:02.165 --> 27:03.708
[door creaks open]

27:03.791 --> 27:05.207
- You see,
I don't think she is.

27:05.291 --> 27:07.499
[door shuts]

27:07.583 --> 27:08.708
- Et voilà.
[laughs]

27:08.791 --> 27:10.249
- Only me!

27:12.249 --> 27:13.749
[quiet plucked string music]

27:13.833 --> 27:15.416
Mr. Mackenzie.

27:15.499 --> 27:17.165
- Mr. Booth.

27:17.249 --> 27:18.749
♪ ♪

27:18.833 --> 27:20.833
- Thank you, John.
That's lovely.

27:20.915 --> 27:27.374
♪ ♪

27:30.040 --> 27:32.207
[chicken clucking,
cow mooing]

27:39.207 --> 27:41.207
[clock ticking]

27:41.291 --> 27:44.624
[clock ringing]

27:44.708 --> 27:45.957
[uneasy music]

27:46.040 --> 27:47.541
- Anne!

27:47.624 --> 27:49.165
- Mm?

27:49.249 --> 27:50.457
I'm here.

27:50.541 --> 27:51.874
- Can you hear that?

27:51.957 --> 27:53.499
[distant groaning]

27:53.583 --> 27:55.249
♪ ♪

27:55.332 --> 27:57.124
- What, the wind?

27:57.207 --> 28:00.040
- No, listen.

28:00.124 --> 28:03.332
You must have heard
that, surely.

28:03.416 --> 28:05.374
- What?
No, I can't...

28:05.457 --> 28:08.165
- [breathing heavily]

28:08.249 --> 28:10.291
♪ ♪

28:10.374 --> 28:12.207
They're talking about you.

28:12.291 --> 28:14.791
- Are they?

28:14.874 --> 28:17.457
And what are they saying
about me?

28:17.541 --> 28:19.416
- Can you really not hear them?

28:19.499 --> 28:21.541
♪ ♪

28:21.624 --> 28:23.416
- Ann, they're not...

28:25.541 --> 28:28.583
I can't hear anything.
There's nothing there.

28:28.666 --> 28:31.082
- You're going to die.

28:31.165 --> 28:34.583
- Well, yes, eventually.
- Don't be glib!

28:34.666 --> 28:36.040
They're going to kill you
as well as me,

28:36.124 --> 28:39.249
and we'll both burn in hell
for all eternity!

28:39.332 --> 28:40.165
- What? No.

28:40.249 --> 28:42.040
- Everlasting torment
in hellfire!

28:42.124 --> 28:45.791
You must have heard that.
Surely, you heard that.

28:45.874 --> 28:48.249
- When you say voices,
how many can you hear?

28:48.332 --> 28:50.291
- Three. Shh!

28:50.374 --> 28:52.207
- Men? Women?

28:52.291 --> 28:54.040
- Men.

28:54.124 --> 28:56.165
Sometimes, there's a woman.

28:56.249 --> 28:57.541
Once, there was a woman.

28:57.624 --> 28:59.541
- Do you recognize the voices--
- Shh, shh, shh!

28:59.624 --> 29:01.583
- No, Ann, do you recognize
the voices?

29:01.666 --> 29:03.708
- No. Shh.

29:03.791 --> 29:05.791
- Are they always
the same voices?

29:05.874 --> 29:09.374
- Oh... they need to shut up.

29:09.457 --> 29:12.791
They're disgusting.
They're so... disgusting.

29:12.874 --> 29:15.666
They're so cruel!

29:15.749 --> 29:16.957
♪ ♪

29:17.040 --> 29:18.457
Yes, it's--

29:18.541 --> 29:20.124
yes, they're always
the same voices,

29:20.207 --> 29:23.165
but why is everyone pretending
not to hear them?

29:24.124 --> 29:26.082
- Where are they?

29:26.165 --> 29:27.583
- In the clock.

29:27.666 --> 29:34.708
♪ ♪

29:37.708 --> 29:39.082
- Shh.
- [whimpers]

29:39.165 --> 29:40.915
Don't go out there.
They'll do something to you.

29:40.999 --> 29:45.165
Just--just shout
through the keyhole.

29:45.249 --> 29:51.416
♪ ♪

29:51.499 --> 29:53.374
- There's no one here, Ann.

29:53.457 --> 29:56.207
- Well, they're spirits.
You can't see them.

29:56.291 --> 29:58.249
Get back in here.

29:58.332 --> 30:00.332
- I'm going to take
the weights out of the clock

30:00.416 --> 30:01.999
to stop it sounding.

30:02.082 --> 30:03.374
That's what's disturbed you.

30:03.457 --> 30:06.457
That and the wind.

30:06.541 --> 30:08.457
- Which art in heaven,
hallowed be thy name.

30:08.541 --> 30:09.541
- Is she all right?

30:09.624 --> 30:11.040
- Thy kingdom come,
thy will be done,

30:11.124 --> 30:12.624
on earth as it is in heaven.

30:12.708 --> 30:15.541
- No, she...

30:15.624 --> 30:17.040
I was in my room next door

30:17.124 --> 30:18.791
and she heard the voices again.

30:18.874 --> 30:19.874
I think someone

30:19.957 --> 30:21.332
should stay with her
in her room.

30:21.416 --> 30:22.666
- And forgive us
our trespasses.

30:22.749 --> 30:24.332
- Would you like to?

30:24.416 --> 30:26.957
- She frightens me.

30:27.040 --> 30:29.957
- I know.
- Catherine?

30:30.040 --> 30:31.457
C-Catherine?

30:31.541 --> 30:32.624
[ominous music]

30:32.708 --> 30:34.624
And lead us not
into temptation,

30:34.708 --> 30:37.541
but deliver us from evil,
for thine is the kingdom

30:37.624 --> 30:39.833
and the power and the glory,
forever and ever.

30:39.915 --> 30:41.874
Amen.

30:41.957 --> 30:43.249
[door handle shuffles]

30:43.332 --> 30:44.833
- Ann?
- [whimpers]

30:44.915 --> 30:47.583
- Shh.

30:47.666 --> 30:49.915
[distant clattering]

30:49.999 --> 30:52.915
Shh, shh.

30:52.999 --> 30:54.332
- Give us this day
our daily bread,

30:54.416 --> 30:56.165
and forgive us
our trespasses...

30:56.249 --> 30:57.207
- Shh.

30:57.291 --> 30:58.999
- As we forgive those
who trespass against us.

30:59.082 --> 31:00.291
- Ann, shh.
- We're here.

31:00.374 --> 31:02.040
- Shh.
- We're both here.

31:02.124 --> 31:04.666
- For thine is the kingdom
and the power and the glory.

31:04.749 --> 31:07.249
- Everything's all right.
You're safe.

31:07.332 --> 31:08.999
- Our father,
who art in heaven,

31:09.082 --> 31:10.249
hallowed be thy name.

31:10.332 --> 31:11.249
- Has anyone written

31:11.332 --> 31:13.332
to Ann's sister in Scotland?

31:15.249 --> 31:16.749
- I don't know.

31:19.124 --> 31:21.791
But someone should.

31:21.874 --> 31:23.207
She...

31:25.874 --> 31:29.040
She is--she isn't
in her right mind.

31:29.124 --> 31:30.541
- I know.

31:32.332 --> 31:34.291
Look, Catherine,

31:34.374 --> 31:36.541
first of all,

31:36.624 --> 31:39.708
you must try not to get
too upset.

31:39.791 --> 31:42.583
You're doing all you can,
you're being very strong,

31:42.666 --> 31:44.791
and it's exactly
what she needs.

31:44.874 --> 31:47.999
And second,

31:48.082 --> 31:50.040
I took her to see
a Dr. Belcombe in York

31:50.124 --> 31:51.708
a number of weeks ago.

31:51.791 --> 31:53.374
He's the brother
of a friend of mine,

31:53.457 --> 31:55.624
and he's a very clever
medical man.

31:55.708 --> 31:59.249
He specializes in exactly
this sort of thing.

31:59.332 --> 32:02.082
I did it without telling
any of Ann's--

32:02.165 --> 32:04.040
your family.

32:04.124 --> 32:06.999
I might take her
over there again.

32:07.082 --> 32:08.791
The thing is--
and I will, of course,

32:08.874 --> 32:10.708
get her sister's consent
this time--

32:10.791 --> 32:15.291
but I would consider it
a great favor

32:15.374 --> 32:18.082
if you didn't tell anyone else

32:18.165 --> 32:19.416
how bad it is--

32:19.499 --> 32:22.332
the aunts and uncles
and other cousins--

32:22.416 --> 32:23.583
because...

32:23.666 --> 32:25.416
[foreboding music]

32:25.499 --> 32:27.291
They'll have her put away.

32:27.374 --> 32:29.666
♪ ♪

32:29.749 --> 32:31.915
And she can get over this.

32:31.999 --> 32:33.541
With the right sort of help,

32:33.624 --> 32:36.874
she may be able to make
a full recovery,

32:36.957 --> 32:39.666
and no one else
need know any different.

32:39.749 --> 32:46.499
♪ ♪

32:46.583 --> 32:50.207
- I've heard the worst things
said about you, Miss Lister.

32:53.082 --> 32:54.874
And I want to apologize

32:54.957 --> 32:57.165
for ever having listened
to them.

32:57.249 --> 33:01.791
I've never seen
such kind, affectionate,

33:01.874 --> 33:03.457
selfless display of friendship

33:03.541 --> 33:05.249
as I saw last night,

33:05.332 --> 33:08.708
and I-I feel ashamed

33:08.791 --> 33:10.999
for ever having doubted you,

33:11.082 --> 33:14.749
or--or thought you had
any motive other than goodness.

33:14.833 --> 33:17.791
[tender music]

33:17.874 --> 33:24.915
♪ ♪

33:35.416 --> 33:36.416
- You've not heard any more

33:36.499 --> 33:38.708
from your sister
since last week?

33:38.791 --> 33:39.999
- No. Why?

33:40.082 --> 33:42.457
- I had a letter
from her friend, Miss Lister.

33:42.541 --> 33:43.666
- You have?

33:43.749 --> 33:45.457
- She wrote to me
because she was mindful

33:45.541 --> 33:48.040
of your delicate health
since your confinement

33:48.124 --> 33:52.791
and didn't want to upset you
"unjudiciously,"

33:52.874 --> 33:55.749
but there seems to be some...
[sighs]

33:55.833 --> 33:58.915
new anxiety about Ann's...

33:58.999 --> 34:00.833
health.

34:00.915 --> 34:03.332
"I don't wish to alarm you
or Mrs. Sutherland,

34:03.416 --> 34:05.040
"but it is my belief
that the advice

34:05.124 --> 34:07.416
"of an experienced
and clever medical man

34:07.499 --> 34:08.499
"is necessary,

34:08.583 --> 34:10.499
and that no time
should be lost."

34:10.583 --> 34:12.374
[baby cooing]

34:12.457 --> 34:14.915
Well, she proposes to take her
to a man in York,

34:14.999 --> 34:18.374
a man she's seen before, but...

34:18.457 --> 34:20.374
I don't know, I wonder...

34:20.457 --> 34:23.332
whether we shouldn't
persuade her to come up here,

34:23.416 --> 34:25.874
where we can look after her.

34:25.957 --> 34:27.541
- Um...

34:27.624 --> 34:28.915
[baby fusses]

34:28.999 --> 34:30.666
She's very fond of Miss Lister,

34:30.749 --> 34:33.541
and she's been very good
to her,

34:33.624 --> 34:34.749
and she's well-connected.

34:34.833 --> 34:36.999
This doctor is probably
very good.

34:37.082 --> 34:39.708
- Yes, but Miss Lister
isn't family, is she,

34:39.791 --> 34:41.374
and we have medical men
in Edinburgh

34:41.457 --> 34:43.708
more than equal
to anyone in York.

34:43.791 --> 34:45.124
Now, you're not fit to travel,

34:45.207 --> 34:47.332
and with Sackville
still in the measles,

34:47.416 --> 34:49.207
he needs you here,

34:49.291 --> 34:52.457
but I could go fetch her.

34:52.541 --> 34:55.374
I could take my mother.

34:55.457 --> 34:58.332
[calm string music]

34:58.416 --> 35:00.249
- Mr. Wortley's latest defeat

35:00.332 --> 35:01.416
in this constituency

35:01.499 --> 35:03.124
was, I'm sad to say,

35:03.207 --> 35:04.666
a foregone conclusion.

35:04.749 --> 35:06.291
Uh, don't misunderstand me.

35:06.374 --> 35:08.957
We are very much
to the right of the question,

35:09.040 --> 35:10.291
aren't we, Mother--

35:10.374 --> 35:12.499
as I'm sure this household is--

35:12.583 --> 35:14.541
but it has to be said,

35:14.624 --> 35:15.999
he didn't put up
a very good fight

35:16.082 --> 35:17.082
at the hustings.

35:17.165 --> 35:18.124
Were you there?

35:18.207 --> 35:20.165
[laughing]
Oh, he looked terrified.

35:20.249 --> 35:24.874
Now, can we be squeezing
any more tea out of that pot?

35:24.957 --> 35:27.791
[tranquil music]

35:27.874 --> 35:30.124
- I don't want to go living
in Halifax

35:30.207 --> 35:31.207
with Miss Thing.

35:31.291 --> 35:32.583
- [laughs]

35:32.666 --> 35:34.416
- I know I'd be learning
a trade,

35:34.499 --> 35:36.291
but she's such an old fossil.

35:36.374 --> 35:37.624
- [laughs]

35:37.708 --> 35:39.499
- There'd be no fun.

35:39.583 --> 35:43.291
We always have fun
at our house after tea.

35:43.374 --> 35:45.082
♪ ♪

35:45.165 --> 35:46.874
Do you at yours?

35:46.957 --> 35:49.165
♪ ♪

35:49.249 --> 35:51.040
- Uh, since me dad went, yeah.

35:52.541 --> 35:54.457
♪ ♪

35:54.541 --> 35:56.332
Miss Lister said,

35:56.416 --> 35:57.666
once I get tenancy,

35:57.749 --> 36:00.666
and I'll be 18 by then,

36:00.749 --> 36:05.040
she'd prefer it if I...

36:05.124 --> 36:06.666
if I--if I got married.

36:06.749 --> 36:08.332
♪ ♪

36:08.416 --> 36:09.666
Said she likes
her people married.

36:09.749 --> 36:14.165
It--it makes them
more settled and reliable.

36:14.249 --> 36:16.499
[laughs]

36:16.583 --> 36:18.708
- Is that right?

36:18.791 --> 36:20.291
- Someone told me
she had this tenant once

36:20.374 --> 36:21.999
who said
he'd never get married.

36:22.082 --> 36:22.957
Then she found out

36:23.040 --> 36:24.708
he'd got this lass
from Northowram

36:24.791 --> 36:26.499
in the family way,

36:26.583 --> 36:27.499
done nowt about it,

36:27.583 --> 36:29.332
so she threw him off the land

36:29.416 --> 36:31.499
and offered to horse-whip him.

36:31.583 --> 36:33.666
[both laugh]

36:33.749 --> 36:39.291
♪ ♪

36:39.374 --> 36:41.374
- Do you want to marry me?

36:41.457 --> 36:46.040
♪ ♪

36:46.124 --> 36:48.708
- I don't think
your dad would like it.

36:48.791 --> 36:52.708
I think he'd think
I wasn't good enough for you.

36:52.791 --> 36:56.833
- Well, yeah,
but he married my mother.

36:56.915 --> 36:58.583
Her mother and father
wouldn't speak to her

36:58.666 --> 36:59.541
for years after,

36:59.624 --> 37:01.874
marrying a land steward's son.

37:01.957 --> 37:03.165
- Really?

37:03.249 --> 37:06.957
But you live in that big house.

37:07.040 --> 37:08.583
- Yeah, only 'cause
it was standing empty,

37:08.666 --> 37:09.957
and Miss Walker said
it'd be better

37:10.040 --> 37:12.999
for it to be lived in.

37:13.082 --> 37:15.624
- You wouldn't want
to live at our house.

37:15.708 --> 37:18.040
- Why wouldn't I?

37:18.124 --> 37:20.541
I could help out on the farm,

37:20.624 --> 37:23.457
I could teach little ones
how to read and write...

37:23.541 --> 37:25.040
- You could teach me,

37:25.124 --> 37:27.791
so when I'm signing tenancy,
I'm not just putting a cross.

37:27.874 --> 37:29.165
- [laughs]

37:29.249 --> 37:31.124
[bell rings]

37:31.207 --> 37:33.374
- Oh, heck.

37:33.457 --> 37:35.583
I'm gonna be late.

37:35.666 --> 37:37.583
We're building the bridge
over the Simplon Pass

37:37.666 --> 37:39.291
up at Shibden.

37:39.374 --> 37:41.583
- Over the what?

37:41.666 --> 37:43.416
- It's in Switzerland.

37:45.874 --> 37:50.791
- Well, I thought
you were proposing to me.

37:50.874 --> 37:53.915
- Well...

37:53.999 --> 37:55.915
what do you think?

37:55.999 --> 38:01.416
- Well, I think,
if you're serious,

38:01.499 --> 38:04.915
you'd have to speak
to my father.

38:04.999 --> 38:06.416
[jaunty music]

38:06.499 --> 38:08.999
- Mr. Washington's
been looking for you.

38:09.082 --> 38:11.291
He says there are a lot of men
up at Brierley Hill

38:11.374 --> 38:13.040
filling in the Rawsons'
Willy Hill pit.

38:13.124 --> 38:14.708
He says they're demolishing
all the sheds

38:14.791 --> 38:16.082
and pulling up the access road.

38:16.165 --> 38:17.915
- The access road's on my land.

38:17.999 --> 38:19.457
- That's what--

38:19.541 --> 38:22.291
our land, yes.

38:22.374 --> 38:23.541
That's what
Mr. Washington said.

38:23.624 --> 38:27.457
He said they've got no right
to touch the... road.

38:27.541 --> 38:29.957
And you missed Mr. Abbott
and his mother.

38:30.040 --> 38:31.874
♪ ♪

38:31.957 --> 38:32.957
[door closes]

38:33.040 --> 38:34.499
- I'm doing
what I've been told to do.

38:34.583 --> 38:35.791
- But that road
is on Shibden land,

38:35.874 --> 38:37.165
whether you like it or not.

38:37.249 --> 38:39.457
And when Miss Lister--
- You can tell her yourself.

38:39.541 --> 38:40.999
- What's going on?

38:41.082 --> 38:43.291
- Oh, fucking hell, I'm not
talking to that bloody Jack.

38:43.374 --> 38:44.249
- What's happening?

38:44.332 --> 38:45.457
- Rawsons have called
the pit in.

38:45.541 --> 38:47.499
- What's Hinscliffe doing here?

38:47.583 --> 38:50.541
- Well, apparently, right,
it's in the terms

38:50.624 --> 38:51.915
of his arrangement
with the Rawsons

38:51.999 --> 38:54.791
that once the Rawsons deem
the beds to be exhausted,

38:54.915 --> 38:56.499
he, Hinscliffe,

38:56.583 --> 38:58.374
is obliged to fill in the pit
and make it safe,

38:58.457 --> 38:59.957
and then demolish
the outbuildings

39:00.040 --> 39:01.249
so they can sell off the stone.

39:01.332 --> 39:03.332
- That road is on Shibden land.
That's my stone.

39:03.416 --> 39:04.457
- Yes, I know.
That's why I--

39:04.541 --> 39:05.624
- Does he know that?

39:05.708 --> 39:07.291
- Well, he's saying it's in
his contract with Rawson

39:07.374 --> 39:09.249
to decommission the road
along with everything else.

39:09.332 --> 39:10.791
- Well, that's wrong,
the pit might be

39:10.874 --> 39:12.124
on Rawson's land,

39:12.207 --> 39:13.624
but the access road is my land.

39:13.708 --> 39:14.583
I may want it.

39:14.666 --> 39:16.749
I certainly want
the value of my stone.

39:16.833 --> 39:18.165
Hinscliffe!
- Uh-uh--

39:18.249 --> 39:19.165
Be careful, ma'am.

39:19.249 --> 39:20.416
- What?
- He's not in a good mood.

39:20.499 --> 39:22.833
- Oh, that's a coincidence.
Neither am I.

39:22.915 --> 39:24.666
- The Rawsons' beds
are exhausted,

39:24.749 --> 39:25.833
but his isn't.

39:25.915 --> 39:28.082
This is the only access
he's got to it,

39:28.165 --> 39:30.915
and financially,
it's a bad day for him,

39:30.999 --> 39:33.541
and I know
you were never going to,

39:33.624 --> 39:34.999
but if you'd sold him
that acre of land

39:35.082 --> 39:36.374
he was after
down at Listerwick,

39:36.457 --> 39:37.957
he'd never have had to do
a rubbish deal

39:38.040 --> 39:39.165
over this pit of Rawson's.

39:39.249 --> 39:40.791
- I can't help that.
Business is business.

39:40.874 --> 39:42.583
- Yes, but I-I'm just saying

39:42.666 --> 39:44.666
that's why he might be rather
less than civil to y--

39:44.749 --> 39:46.791
- Hinscliffe!

39:46.874 --> 39:48.541
You tell your men
to leave that road alone.

39:48.624 --> 39:50.040
That's my land.

39:50.124 --> 39:51.833
I don't care
what your arrangement is

39:51.915 --> 39:54.207
with Rawson.

39:54.291 --> 39:55.207
Anyone who pulls up

39:55.291 --> 39:56.708
another single one
of those stones

39:56.791 --> 39:59.874
will have the inconvenience
of a trip to Wakefield jail!

39:59.957 --> 40:02.874
[tense music]

40:02.957 --> 40:06.291
♪ ♪

40:06.374 --> 40:09.207
[jaunty music]

40:09.291 --> 40:14.791
♪ ♪

40:14.874 --> 40:16.708
- Get a court order
to stop them pulling up

40:16.791 --> 40:18.791
and selling any stone
belonging to Shibden land.

40:18.915 --> 40:20.457
Course we can.
That's not a problem.

40:20.541 --> 40:22.791
But there's rather more to it.

40:22.874 --> 40:23.957
- What?

40:24.040 --> 40:25.583
- Mr. Rawson appears
to have found out

40:25.666 --> 40:28.291
that Hinscliffe
was his rival for your coal.

40:28.374 --> 40:29.833
- How?

40:29.915 --> 40:32.583
- And that the price
was so inflated

40:32.666 --> 40:34.791
because he only wanted
the one acre,

40:34.874 --> 40:37.291
so he's lashing out
at Hinscliffe,

40:37.374 --> 40:38.874
and he's just come back
to me this morning

40:38.957 --> 40:41.291
with a much lower offer--

40:41.374 --> 40:42.915
Mr. Rawson has,

40:42.999 --> 40:44.791
and he's making it
utterly plain

40:44.874 --> 40:46.624
that he won't agree
to your clauses either,

40:46.708 --> 40:48.666
which we know
are perfectly legitimate

40:48.749 --> 40:51.999
and you're absolutely right
to insist upon, but--

40:52.082 --> 40:53.749
and, for some reason,

40:53.833 --> 40:55.457
he no longer seems to fear

40:55.541 --> 40:58.499
that you'll sink your own pit.

40:58.583 --> 41:01.124
Is that, uh, the case?

41:02.874 --> 41:05.791
[sedate music]

41:05.874 --> 41:09.374
- For the moment, yes.

41:09.457 --> 41:13.541
That isn't an option anymore.

41:13.624 --> 41:15.791
But not for the reason
he thinks.

41:15.874 --> 41:18.499
♪ ♪

41:18.583 --> 41:20.833
The strategy
for inflating the price

41:20.915 --> 41:22.624
was arrived at solely to cover

41:22.708 --> 41:23.749
what the Rawsons had stolen.

41:23.833 --> 41:25.291
I wasn't being mercenary!

41:25.374 --> 41:27.165
- I know that, Anne.

41:27.249 --> 41:29.541
- I don't have to sign
this agreement with him.

41:29.624 --> 41:31.957
- No, I don't think you should.

41:32.040 --> 41:34.708
But then he'll continue
to steal your coal anyway,

41:34.791 --> 41:38.749
if you can't get down there
to keep an eye on him yourself.

41:38.833 --> 41:40.791
Of course, you could sell
to someone else,

41:40.874 --> 41:44.874
but, uh, then
what's stolen is gone.

41:44.957 --> 41:47.165
There'd be no recompense
for that.

41:47.249 --> 41:51.165
♪ ♪

41:51.249 --> 41:52.833
I know it's easier said
than done,

41:52.915 --> 41:56.999
but, uh, try not to take this
too personally.

41:57.082 --> 41:59.666
You're not the first person
he's swindled,

41:59.749 --> 42:02.291
and you won't be the last.

42:02.374 --> 42:03.874
Sickening, isn't it?

42:03.957 --> 42:05.541
♪ ♪

42:05.624 --> 42:09.082
- You could always
reopen Listerwick

42:09.165 --> 42:11.541
down at Mytholm.

42:11.624 --> 42:13.999
It'd be half the expense
of sinking a new pit.

42:14.082 --> 42:15.791
- It has to be up there
on the hill

42:15.874 --> 42:17.416
to prove the trespass.

42:17.499 --> 42:19.291
- Oh.

42:19.374 --> 42:21.249
- It has to be a new pit.

42:23.457 --> 42:27.291
- And Miss Walker
definitely isn't...

42:27.374 --> 42:29.040
[somber music]

42:29.124 --> 42:30.874
Mm.

42:30.957 --> 42:36.207
♪ ♪

42:36.291 --> 42:38.499
- ...which art in heaven,
hallowed be thy name.

42:38.583 --> 42:40.708
Thy kingdom come,
thy will be done,

42:40.791 --> 42:42.833
on earth as it is in heaven.

42:42.915 --> 42:44.541
Give us this day
our daily bread

42:44.624 --> 42:46.040
and forgive us our trespasses,

42:46.124 --> 42:47.082
as we forgive those

42:47.165 --> 42:48.416
who trespass against us,

42:48.499 --> 42:49.833
and lead us not
into temptation,

42:49.915 --> 42:51.040
but deliver us from evil,

42:51.124 --> 42:52.124
for thine is the kingdom,

42:52.207 --> 42:53.915
the power, and the glory,
forever and ever.

42:53.999 --> 42:55.124
Amen.

42:55.207 --> 42:56.082
Our father...

42:56.165 --> 42:57.165
Hallowed be thy name...

42:57.249 --> 42:58.583
Forever and ever.

42:58.666 --> 42:59.541
Amen.

42:59.624 --> 43:00.708
And forgive us our trespasses,

43:00.791 --> 43:02.915
as we forgive those
who trespass against us.

43:02.999 --> 43:08.999
♪ ♪

43:10.874 --> 43:12.416
- Ann.

43:12.499 --> 43:15.583
♪ ♪

43:15.666 --> 43:16.999
Ann?

43:17.082 --> 43:21.416
♪ ♪

43:21.499 --> 43:23.457
I've got to go.

43:23.541 --> 43:26.416
I've got things to do.

43:26.499 --> 43:28.207
♪ ♪

43:28.291 --> 43:29.999
- Will you come back?

43:30.082 --> 43:32.749
♪ ♪

43:32.833 --> 43:34.957
- Yes, of course.

43:35.040 --> 43:36.082
♪ ♪

43:36.165 --> 43:38.082
How I long
to be creditably free

43:38.165 --> 43:41.124
from all this madness,

43:41.207 --> 43:43.791
and yet, I don't know
how it is...

43:43.874 --> 43:46.749
Whenever I see the girl,

43:46.874 --> 43:50.457
she always manages
to unhinge me.

43:50.541 --> 43:52.624
- My dear Miss Lister,

43:52.708 --> 43:54.833
the soonest I find
I can travel south

43:54.915 --> 43:56.499
is a fortnight on Friday.

43:56.583 --> 43:58.291
With luck,
I shall reach Halifax

43:58.374 --> 43:59.416
on the Monday,

43:59.499 --> 44:00.457
when my mother and I

44:00.541 --> 44:01.541
shall collect Miss Walker

44:01.624 --> 44:02.957
and bring her back up
to Scotland

44:03.040 --> 44:04.082
to be with her sister,

44:04.165 --> 44:05.666
when we will endeavor to find

44:05.749 --> 44:06.874
the best medical man

44:06.957 --> 44:08.541
Edinburgh has to offer.

44:08.624 --> 44:11.291
My wife is writing separately
to her sister

44:11.374 --> 44:14.541
to say my journey
is primarily one of business,

44:14.624 --> 44:15.957
but to suggest
at the same time

44:16.040 --> 44:19.332
she takes the opportunity
to return north with me.

44:19.416 --> 44:20.833
When you read this letter,

44:20.915 --> 44:22.249
she should also be
in possession

44:22.332 --> 44:25.499
of the letter from her sister
proposing the idea.

44:25.583 --> 44:27.583
♪ ♪

44:27.666 --> 44:29.499
- I think it's a good idea,

44:29.583 --> 44:32.583
a change of air,
a change of scenery,

44:32.666 --> 44:35.624
and think how much you'll enjoy
seeing the children,

44:35.708 --> 44:39.332
little Sackville and Alice
and the new baby,

44:39.416 --> 44:40.749
and Elizabeth will be so happy

44:40.833 --> 44:43.332
to have you there again
after all this time.

44:45.124 --> 44:47.082
- What do you think?

44:48.791 --> 44:51.207
- The medical establishment
in Edinburgh is very good.

44:51.291 --> 44:55.165
Your sister's right,
and Catherine's right too.

44:55.249 --> 44:57.957
A change of air is exactly
what Dr. Belcombe prescribed.

44:58.040 --> 45:01.833
- He meant if I went to Paris
and Rome with you.

45:01.915 --> 45:03.124
- Yes, but...

45:05.583 --> 45:08.416
The time for that is gone now,

45:08.499 --> 45:11.957
and you need to be
a lot better for that.

45:12.040 --> 45:13.666
This, for the moment,

45:13.749 --> 45:15.541
would seem to be
by far the best.

45:15.624 --> 45:17.624
- I thought you were
going to take me

45:17.708 --> 45:19.040
to see Dr. Belcombe again
in York.

45:19.124 --> 45:20.874
I thought that was why
you'd written to her,

45:20.957 --> 45:22.541
for permission to take me.

45:22.624 --> 45:25.541
- I did, I suggested it, but...

45:25.624 --> 45:27.499
obviously, they think
this is a better idea.

45:27.583 --> 45:29.082
- They?
- Your sister.

45:29.165 --> 45:31.915
- They know nothing about me.
- Oh, Ann.

45:31.999 --> 45:33.040
She's your sister.

45:33.124 --> 45:35.999
- We can travel together
when you're better.

45:36.082 --> 45:38.541
There's plenty of time
for that.

45:38.624 --> 45:41.541
- But you'll still go to Europe
come spring?

45:44.207 --> 45:47.416
- I can't imagine
I would get away until May,

45:47.499 --> 45:50.165
at the earliest, but...

45:50.249 --> 45:53.249
yes, that is still
my intention.

45:53.332 --> 45:56.165
- With whom?

45:56.249 --> 45:59.207
- No one.
I'd go alone.

46:01.499 --> 46:04.624
- Really?
- Well, a man and a maid.

46:04.708 --> 46:07.499
- Do ladies do that?

46:07.583 --> 46:11.249
- Not as a rule, no.
- Will you stay tonight?

46:11.332 --> 46:14.291
[melancholy string music]

46:14.374 --> 46:17.833
♪ ♪

46:17.915 --> 46:20.666
- Catherine...

46:20.749 --> 46:22.624
Miss Rawson, would you mind
if I had a few moments

46:22.708 --> 46:23.666
alone with Miss Walker?

46:23.749 --> 46:25.040
- Oh, no.

46:25.124 --> 46:26.416
Of course not.

46:26.499 --> 46:28.624
Oh, I should get some fresh air

46:28.708 --> 46:31.457
before the light falls.

46:31.541 --> 46:33.332
[door clicks open]

46:38.374 --> 46:40.541
- I've lost you, haven't I?

46:40.624 --> 46:43.624
♪ ♪

46:43.708 --> 46:46.165
- You needn't have.

46:46.249 --> 46:49.040
♪ ♪

46:49.124 --> 46:52.207
- If I go to Scotland,
I'll never see you again.

46:52.291 --> 46:54.332
♪ ♪

46:54.416 --> 46:56.957
- That's not necessarily
the case.

46:57.040 --> 47:02.040
♪ ♪

47:02.124 --> 47:03.332
I bought a ring.

47:03.416 --> 47:05.499
I know you told me
not to send for it,

47:05.583 --> 47:07.874
but I already had, so...

47:07.957 --> 47:09.457
♪ ♪

47:09.541 --> 47:11.165
Really is rather splendid.

47:11.249 --> 47:13.291
Be loath to send it back.

47:13.374 --> 47:20.416
♪ ♪

47:29.999 --> 47:32.082
Will you accept it?

47:33.624 --> 47:36.416
Will you accept me?

47:36.499 --> 47:38.374
Will you take the sacrament
with me

47:38.457 --> 47:42.165
and live with me at Shibden
and mean it,

47:42.249 --> 47:44.165
and not just say it

47:44.249 --> 47:46.207
because you're scared
to be alone tonight,

47:46.291 --> 47:49.124
or because it's expedient,
and then...

47:49.207 --> 47:51.291
say something else
in the morning?

47:51.374 --> 47:54.416
[building string music]

47:54.499 --> 48:01.624
♪ ♪

48:03.833 --> 48:05.374
- [sobs quietly]

48:05.457 --> 48:10.874
♪ ♪

48:10.957 --> 48:14.499
I can't.

48:14.583 --> 48:17.124
[crying]
I can't.

48:17.207 --> 48:24.291
♪ ♪

48:26.457 --> 48:28.541
- My dearest Mary,

48:28.624 --> 48:30.541
after I've taken Thomas Beech
and Eugénie

48:30.624 --> 48:32.957
over to the Norcliffes
to collect my carriage,

48:33.040 --> 48:35.374
I shall go to London
for two weeks

48:35.457 --> 48:37.374
before I cross the water.

48:37.457 --> 48:40.207
If you were able
to join me there in London,

48:40.291 --> 48:41.957
if Charles can manage
without you,

48:42.040 --> 48:44.082
for some or all
of those two weeks,

48:44.165 --> 48:47.791
I would, as always,

48:47.874 --> 48:49.499
count it as a great blessing

48:49.583 --> 48:50.791
to see you.

48:50.874 --> 48:54.749
You ask me if I'm traveling
with "my little friend,"

48:54.833 --> 48:56.708
which I am not.

48:56.791 --> 48:59.749
More of this
if and when I see you.

48:59.833 --> 49:06.833
♪ ♪

49:13.040 --> 49:14.957
- Are you ill as well, Marian?

49:15.040 --> 49:16.791
- No, I feel perfectly well,
thank you, Aunt.

49:16.874 --> 49:18.708
[dish clinks]

49:22.541 --> 49:24.291
- You're quiet.

49:27.749 --> 49:29.791
- I've not heard anything
from Mr. Abbott

49:29.874 --> 49:31.457
for nearly three weeks.

49:33.457 --> 49:34.999
- Oh, dear.

49:35.082 --> 49:37.915
Do you think he's--
- He did mention, as he left,

49:37.999 --> 49:38.957
that he'd visited twice,

49:39.040 --> 49:40.124
and both times,

49:40.207 --> 49:42.332
Miss Lister had failed
to appear.

49:42.416 --> 49:44.124
- It's you he's interested in,
not me.

49:44.207 --> 49:47.082
- You are Miss Lister
of Shibden Hall!

49:47.165 --> 49:48.165
You own the place,

49:48.249 --> 49:50.416
as you never tire
of reminding everyone!

49:50.499 --> 49:52.666
It is clearly a snub,

49:52.749 --> 49:55.374
especially when a place
has been set at the table,

49:55.457 --> 49:57.499
if you choose not to turn up!

49:57.583 --> 49:59.957
I can only assume
he felt particularly humiliated

50:00.040 --> 50:01.040
in front of his mother,

50:01.124 --> 50:03.708
who was very polite
and very well-mannered.

50:03.791 --> 50:06.249
- Yes, she was very p--

50:06.332 --> 50:08.416
she was very quiet.

50:09.915 --> 50:12.332
- He isn't good enough for you.

50:12.416 --> 50:13.749
- You just don't want me
to get married

50:13.833 --> 50:15.207
because it frightens you
that one day,

50:15.291 --> 50:17.499
I could have a greater claim
to Shibden than you.

50:17.583 --> 50:18.833
[footsteps approaching]

50:18.915 --> 50:20.874
- [knocks]
Sorry, ma'am.

50:20.957 --> 50:23.915
[melancholy music]

50:23.999 --> 50:27.082
♪ ♪

50:27.165 --> 50:28.332
- My dearest,

50:28.416 --> 50:30.165
Captain Sutherland
and his mother

50:30.249 --> 50:31.624
arrived last night.

50:31.708 --> 50:33.165
I write in utter misery.

50:33.249 --> 50:36.791
What I said to you last,
I bitterly repent.

50:36.874 --> 50:38.791
If ever the prayers
of so true a friend

50:38.874 --> 50:40.457
may avail for another,

50:40.541 --> 50:42.249
may yours be heard for me,

50:42.332 --> 50:43.249
that the gate of mercy

50:43.332 --> 50:45.833
may not be forever closed
upon me,

50:45.915 --> 50:48.874
for I am wretchedness itself.

50:48.957 --> 50:52.666
♪ ♪

50:52.749 --> 50:54.124
- I'm going out.

50:54.207 --> 51:01.291
♪ ♪

51:09.332 --> 51:11.541
- Ma'am.

51:11.624 --> 51:17.499
♪ ♪

51:17.583 --> 51:19.583
Miss Lister, sir.

51:19.666 --> 51:21.291
Ma'am.

51:22.957 --> 51:24.416
[door shuts]

51:24.499 --> 51:25.624
- How do you do, ma'am?

51:25.708 --> 51:28.749
Captain Sutherland.
We've corresponded.

51:28.833 --> 51:30.416
- Ah.

51:30.499 --> 51:32.915
- And, uh, this is my mother.

51:32.999 --> 51:35.291
- How do you do, ma'am?

51:35.374 --> 51:37.040
- I'm sorry the weather
wasn't kinder to you

51:37.124 --> 51:38.165
while you were on the road.

51:38.249 --> 51:39.207
Where's Miss Walker?

51:39.291 --> 51:42.249
- Upstairs, packing--
supposed to be.

51:42.332 --> 51:44.082
- Well, she doesn't seem
as eager to go

51:44.165 --> 51:46.541
as we are to have her.

51:46.624 --> 51:51.249
Miss Rawson has explained
the, uh, delicacy

51:51.332 --> 51:52.249
of the situation

51:52.332 --> 51:55.791
with regard to the family,

51:55.874 --> 51:58.249
and I would like
to thank you, Miss Lister,

51:58.332 --> 51:59.874
on behalf of my wife
and myself,

51:59.957 --> 52:02.499
for your sensitivity
and kindness

52:02.583 --> 52:06.749
and sound judgment
in the matter.

52:06.833 --> 52:09.291
- I believe she can make
a full recovery,

52:09.374 --> 52:10.833
given the right sort of help.

52:10.915 --> 52:13.124
She's perfectly herself
on all subjects

52:13.207 --> 52:15.541
but that of
religious despondency.

52:15.624 --> 52:19.583
- We've been recommended
a Dr. Hamilton, ma'am,

52:19.666 --> 52:21.165
in Edinburgh.

52:21.249 --> 52:23.708
A lady's physician.

52:25.624 --> 52:27.332
- What's your itinerary,
Captain Sutherland?

52:27.416 --> 52:29.416
- We plan to set off
first thing in the morning.

52:29.499 --> 52:31.165
If we leave here by 10:00,

52:31.249 --> 52:33.541
we can be in Edinburgh
by Thursday evening

52:33.624 --> 52:35.874
and Fortrose
by Saturday night.

52:37.874 --> 52:39.332
- Should I go and see if...

52:39.416 --> 52:41.124
- Might be as well.

52:41.207 --> 52:44.291
[tender music]

52:44.374 --> 52:51.457
♪ ♪

53:02.082 --> 53:03.999
- I don't want to go.

53:04.082 --> 53:06.082
- I know.

53:06.165 --> 53:08.374
I know.

53:08.457 --> 53:09.749
- Stay tonight.

53:09.833 --> 53:11.874
Promise me you'll stay tonight.

53:11.957 --> 53:15.583
♪ ♪

53:15.666 --> 53:17.999
- I will.

53:18.082 --> 53:19.416
I will, I promise.

53:19.499 --> 53:21.082
- Oh...

53:21.165 --> 53:23.416
♪ ♪

53:27.249 --> 53:30.291
[gasping, moaning]

53:43.624 --> 53:45.332
Anne?

53:49.165 --> 53:51.874
Anne?

53:51.957 --> 53:53.999
- It--

53:54.082 --> 53:56.291
- What?
- [sniffs]

54:01.165 --> 54:02.374
Nothing.

54:02.457 --> 54:04.124
- Anne!

54:15.332 --> 54:17.332
- I understand...

54:20.791 --> 54:22.915
Why you can't commit to me.

54:25.249 --> 54:28.583
It's impossible, I know.

54:28.666 --> 54:30.833
How could anyone?

54:30.915 --> 54:32.957
[sniffles]

54:33.040 --> 54:34.708
What am I?

54:37.874 --> 54:39.666
Every day...

54:43.165 --> 54:44.999
Every day,

54:45.082 --> 54:47.457
I rise above it,

54:47.541 --> 54:49.874
the things people say.

54:49.957 --> 54:53.416
I walk into a room
or down a street,

54:53.499 --> 54:56.999
and I see the way
people look at me,

54:57.082 --> 55:00.457
and the things they say,

55:00.541 --> 55:03.416
and I rise above it,

55:03.499 --> 55:08.291
because...
I've trained myself to,

55:08.374 --> 55:10.791
not to see it and hear it,

55:10.874 --> 55:12.791
until it's become
second nature to me,

55:12.874 --> 55:15.541
and I forget...

55:18.207 --> 55:19.624
Just how impossible it is

55:19.708 --> 55:22.124
for someone else
to accept that.

55:22.207 --> 55:25.124
[melancholy music]

55:25.207 --> 55:28.082
[breathes raggedly]

55:30.291 --> 55:33.457
But you came so close.

55:33.541 --> 55:40.624
♪ ♪

55:54.833 --> 56:01.915
♪ ♪

56:18.957 --> 56:20.708
- I wanted to give you this.

56:20.791 --> 56:23.332
♪ ♪

56:23.416 --> 56:24.374
I wrote in it,

56:24.457 --> 56:26.249
in the back.

56:26.332 --> 56:29.874
♪ ♪

56:29.957 --> 56:31.666
For he shall give his angels

56:31.749 --> 56:33.915
charge over thee,

56:33.999 --> 56:37.040
to keep thee in all thy ways.

56:37.124 --> 56:43.624
♪ ♪

56:52.666 --> 56:58.833
♪ ♪

57:02.291 --> 57:04.457
- You are close to Miss Walker,

57:04.541 --> 57:06.749
Miss Lister, ma'am.

57:06.833 --> 57:08.249
I did wonder

57:08.332 --> 57:13.416
if you knew of any love affair
on her mind at present.

57:13.499 --> 57:15.915
- No.

57:15.999 --> 57:17.291
Not that I know of.

57:17.374 --> 57:19.457
- She's never mentioned
my nephew,

57:19.541 --> 57:22.082
Sir Alexander Mackenzie?

57:23.915 --> 57:25.249
- No.

57:25.332 --> 57:29.082
- He proposed to her once,
two years ago,

57:29.165 --> 57:32.957
when she was last in Fortrose.

57:33.040 --> 57:35.749
At first,
he had reason to hope.

57:35.833 --> 57:38.749
She was very civil to him,

57:38.833 --> 57:41.374
but then it was no.

57:43.374 --> 57:44.833
- He must have mistaken
her civility

57:44.915 --> 57:46.957
for something else.

57:47.040 --> 57:48.457
She's always civil.

57:48.541 --> 57:51.374
- He's not a bad man,
Alexander,

57:51.457 --> 57:53.749
and perfectly good-looking,

57:53.833 --> 57:55.583
but he is rather--

57:55.666 --> 57:57.791
and I shouldn't say it--

57:57.874 --> 57:59.957
inept with money,

58:00.040 --> 58:01.624
in the past,

58:01.708 --> 58:05.833
and he has his mother
and his sisters to keep,

58:05.915 --> 58:07.082
but who knows?

58:07.165 --> 58:09.499
He might rise to the occasion.

58:09.583 --> 58:11.124
She could do a lot worse.

58:11.207 --> 58:13.291
It could suit them both.

58:15.541 --> 58:17.666
- I hope Miss Walker
would never marry anyone

58:17.749 --> 58:20.291
to pay their debts.

58:20.374 --> 58:22.999
I trust Captain Sutherland
would deal decisively

58:23.082 --> 58:25.915
with any such fortune-hunters.

58:25.999 --> 58:28.124
- Mother, let's get you in.

58:30.708 --> 58:33.124
- Miss Lister.

58:33.207 --> 58:35.833
- Mrs. Sutherland.

58:35.915 --> 58:38.874
[sedate music]

58:38.957 --> 58:45.915
♪ ♪

59:00.249 --> 59:05.874
♪ ♪

59:08.291 --> 59:11.708
You'll be all right.

59:11.791 --> 59:13.416
Look after yourself.

59:13.499 --> 59:19.374
♪ ♪

59:24.583 --> 59:27.541
[rousing music]

59:27.624 --> 59:31.499
♪ ♪

59:31.583 --> 59:33.291
- Miss Lister.

59:33.374 --> 59:40.457
♪ ♪

59:52.416 --> 59:59.499
♪ ♪

1:00:10.583 --> 1:00:12.749
- ♪ Behind her back,
she's Gentleman Jack ♪

1:00:12.833 --> 1:00:14.999
♪ A Yorkshire lady
of renown ♪

1:00:15.082 --> 1:00:17.165
♪ Ever so fine,
won't toe the line ♪

1:00:17.249 --> 1:00:19.374
♪ Speak her name
and gentlemen frown ♪

1:00:19.457 --> 1:00:21.374
♪ At Shibden Hall,
she had them all ♪

1:00:21.457 --> 1:00:23.708
♪ The fairer sex
fell under her spell ♪

1:00:23.791 --> 1:00:25.915
♪ Dapper and bright,
she held them tight ♪

1:00:25.999 --> 1:00:28.249
♪ Handsome Anne
seduced them well ♪

1:00:28.332 --> 1:00:30.291
♪ Gentleman Jack,
oh, Gentleman Jack ♪

1:00:30.374 --> 1:00:32.124
♪ Watch your back,
you're under attack ♪

1:00:32.207 --> 1:00:34.457
♪ Their husbands are coming,
you'd better start running ♪

1:00:34.541 --> 1:00:36.791
♪ For nobody likes
a Jack-the-lass ♪

1:00:36.874 --> 1:00:38.957
♪ Jack-the-lass,
Jack-the-lass ♪

1:00:39.040 --> 1:00:41.040
♪ No one likes
a Jack-the-lass ♪

1:00:41.124 --> 1:00:43.124
♪ The code is cracked,
your bags are packed ♪

1:00:43.207 --> 1:00:46.040
♪ The knives are out
for Gentleman Jack ♪

1:00:48.749 --> 1:00:50.791
[bright tone]

1:00:53.249 --> 1:00:54.749
ANNE LISTER: I had the promise
of a substantial investment,

1:00:54.833 --> 1:00:55.708
which I no longer have.

1:00:56.207 --> 1:00:58.040
Without it, I'd have to risk
everything, my entire income.

1:00:58.624 --> 1:01:00.583
MARIAN LISTER:
Anne? Is it true...

1:01:00.666 --> 1:01:03.207
that you have given Mr. Rawson
the deeds to Shibden?

1:01:04.541 --> 1:01:06.457
ANNE: Part of me just wants
to run off. Forget about it.

1:01:06.541 --> 1:01:08.957
-That's not like you.
-ANNE: You might be surprised.

1:01:10.165 --> 1:01:12.124
If Mariana and I
ever did get together,

1:01:12.207 --> 1:01:14.165
finally the world
might make sense.

1:01:14.249 --> 1:01:16.999
I still love you.
More than your Ms. Walker.

1:01:17.082 --> 1:01:18.624
(SOBBING) Don't leave me.

1:01:22.541 --> 1:01:24.291
Ann? What have you done?

1:01:24.374 --> 1:01:26.165
-ANN WALKER: I...
-(GASPS)
